This paper discusses the impact of DNS-over-HTTPS (DoH) and DNS-over-TLS (DoT) on the performance of DNS and content delivery, which falls under the category of computer networks (cs.NI). The paper also addresses the privacy risks associated with conventional DNS, which could be classified under computer security and cryptography (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper analyzes the implications of DoH and DoT on content delivery, which could be categorized under social and information networks (cs.SI) and distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). Finally, the paper discusses opportunities to improve DNS performance, which could be classified under cybernetics (cs.CY).
